Two Basque separatist group ETA members were arrested for transporting explosives to Madrid before the March 2004 bombings, receiving 22-year jail sentences each.
Accused of placing bombs on commuter trains, Irkus Badillo and Gorka Vidal aimed to "sow panic" in Madrid.
Zougam, linked to a Spanish Al-Qaeda cell, was arrested for his role in the attacks.
The trial of 29 suspects, including Ahmed, the alleged mastermind, began amid tight security.
Ahmed denies all charges related to the deadliest Al-Qaeda attacks in Europe, which killed 191 and injured 2,000.
